SIMPLE: embargo
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Embargo
<hw>Em*bar"go</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Embargoes</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Sp., fr.
<ets>embargar</ets> to arrest, restrain; pref. <ets>em-</ets> (L.
<ets>in</ets>) + Sp. <ets>barra</ets> bar, akin to F. <ets>barre</ets>
bar. See <er>Bar</er>.]</ety> <def>An edict or order of the government
prohibiting the departure of ships of commerce from some or all of the
ports within its dominions; a prohibition to sail.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ If the <xex>embargo</xex> is laid on an enemy's ships,
it is called a <xex>hostile embargo</xex>; if on the ships belonging to
citizens of the embargoing state, it is called a <xex>civil
embargo</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embargo</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Embargo
<hw>Em*bar"go</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Embargoed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Embargoing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To lay an embargo on and thus
detain; to prohibit from leaving port; -- said of ships, also of
commerce and goods.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Embark</ent>⟦br⟧
